Just now

--

A few months ago I was reviewing a pull request where a teammate had written a switch expression over a class hierarchy. Three subtypes, a default arm that just threw InvalidOperationException(“unreachable”), and a comment that said “remember to update this if we add a new shape.” Two sprints later somebody added a fourth shape, forgot the switch, and we shipped a bug that only showed up in production. I have seen this exact pattern on almost every project I have worked on. The compiler could not help us because it did not know the hierarchy was finite.
That is the kind of papercut .NET 11 and C# 15 are going after. The headline language features (union types and closed hierarchies) exist precisely so the compiler can tell you “you forgot a case” at build time. But the release is much bigger than the language. The runtime got a new async model, the JIT learned a pile of new tricks, the libraries picked up genuinely useful APIs like JSON Lines and full outer joins, and the SDK keeps making the file-based app experience nicer.
.NET 11 is in preview right now, with the final release expected in November 2026, and I have been living in the preview SDKs to write this. Everything below is pulled straight from the official dotnet/core release notes and the dotnet/docs repo, newest preview first.
Let’s take a closer look at the features expected to come with C# 15 and .NET 11!
Union types and closed hierarchies (the C# 15 headliners)
Let me start with the two features that fix my PR story. A union type represents a value that is exactly one of a fixed set of case types. You declare it with the union keyword, and the compiler enforces that your switch expressions cover every case. No default arm, no “unreachable” comment, no production surprise.
public record class Cat(string Name);
public record class Dog(string Name);
public record class Bird(string Name);public union Pet(Cat, Dog, Bird);
string Describe(Pet pet) => pet switch
{
Dog d => $"dog: {d.Name}",
Cat c => $"cat: {c.Name}",
Bird b => $"bird: {b.Name}",
// No default needed. Add a fourth case type and this won't compile until you handle it.
};
Closed hierarchies solve the same exhaustiveness problem for inheritance. You mark a base class closed, which means it can only be derived from inside its own assembly. Because the compiler now knows every direct descendant, a switch that handles all of them is exhaustive, and you can drop the default arm. A closed class is implicitly abstract, and the closed modifier is a contextual keyword, so it will not break existing identifiers named “closed.”
public closed record class GateState;
public record class Closed : GateState;
public record class Open(float Percent) : GateState;string Describe(GateState state) => state switch
{
Closed => "closed",
Open(var percent) => $"{percent}% open",
// Every direct descendant is handled, so no warning and no default arm.
};
Now the honest caveat, because the previews move fast. In Preview 5 the runtime ships the UnionAttribute and IUnion types for unions, but it does not yet ship System.Runtime.CompilerServices.ClosedAttribute. Until it does, any project that uses the closed modifier has to declare the attribute itself as a small polyfill. The docs spell this out, and it is the kind of detail that will quietly change in a later preview, so check the current release notes when you try it.
// Required polyfill in preview 5 if you use `closed`:
namespace System.Runtime.CompilerServices;[AttributeUsage(AttributeTargets.Class, AllowMultiple = false, Inherited = false)]
public sealed class ClosedAttribute : Attribute { }
These two features had a staged rollout across the previews. Compiler support for unions arrived in Preview 2, IDE support improved in Preview 3, and Preview 5 brought closed hierarchies plus union declarations and patterns together. Some pieces of the original union proposal are not implemented yet, so treat this as a feature that is still filling in.
Collection expression arguments and the memory-safety work
The third C# 15 feature is one I reach for constantly: collection expression arguments. Collection expressions (the [1, 2, 3] syntax) are great, but until now you could not tell the compiler anything about the underlying collection, like “pre-size this list” or “use a case-insensitive comparer.” C# 15 adds a with(…) element as the first element of a collection expression to pass arguments straight to the constructor or factory.
string[] values = ["one", "two", "three"];// Pass a capacity to the List<T> constructor.
List<string> names = [with(capacity: values.Length * 2), .. values];
// Pass a comparer to the HashSet<T> constructor.
HashSet<string> set = [with(StringComparer.OrdinalIgnoreCase), "Hello", "HELLO", "hello"];
// set has one element because the three strings compare equal under OrdinalIgnoreCase.
This shipped in Preview 1 and is the most “use it tomorrow” of the language features. I have already replaced a handful of new List<T>(capacity) followed by AddRange blocks with a single collection expression, and the intent reads better.
The fourth feature is the start of a longer journey: redefining memory safety. The goal is to tie the unsafe context to the operations that actually touch unmanaged memory, rather than to whole blocks of otherwise-safe code. In C# 15’s first step, when you compile with the preview language version, declaring a pointer type, taking an address with &, using a fixed statement, converting a stackalloc to a pointer, and sizeof on an unmanaged type no longer require an unsafe context. The operations that read or write through the pointer still do.
int number = 42;
int* pointer = &number; // Allowed outside `unsafe` now.unsafe
{
Console.WriteLine(*pointer); // Dereference still requires `unsafe`.
}
The bigger pieces (the requires-unsafe member model where unsafe on a member pushes the audit obligation to the caller, plus a safe contextual keyword) are coming in later previews. This is a multi-release effort, so do not expect the whole story in .NET 11.
Runtime and JIT: faster code you don’t have to write
Here is where you get wins for free. Runtime-async is the marquee runtime feature. Instead of the compiler generating state machines for your async methods, the runtime handles async natively, which produces cleaner stack traces and lower overhead. By Preview 4 the runtime libraries themselves were compiled with runtime-async=on, so they no longer carry compiler-generated state machines. And it is on by default: as of .NET 11, runtime-async no longer needs <EnablePreviewFeatures>true</EnablePreviewFeatures>, and the switch to disable it at the runtime level was removed in Preview 4.
Preview 5 kept sharpening the suspension and resumption paths. The standout is that methods optimized by on-stack replacement now resume directly into optimized code instead of taking the slow general-purpose transition. The release notes put the old transition overhead at roughly 10x to 20x, so this is a real improvement for hot async paths, and a ValueTask backed by IValueTaskSource now reuses its continuation on suspend, removing an allocation.
The JIT also keeps getting smarter in ways that touch ordinary code. A few from the recent previews:

• Redundant span bounds checks are eliminated in more cases, like loops that repeatedly slice a fixed-width prefix, or reading the final few bytes with span.Slice(span.Length, constant).

• string.Equals and ReadOnlySpan<T>.SequenceEqual can be constant-folded when both operands are known constants, which matters a lot after inlining brings two constants into the same method body.

• On x86 with AVX-512 or AVX10.2, float-to- long/ulong casts now use hardware conversion instructions instead of a runtime helper call.

• Arm intrinsics gained native-integer overloads and new SVE2 predicate-generation methods.
// The JIT now drops the extra range-check block from loops like this,
// no source change required.
int Sum(ReadOnlySpan<int> data)
{
Vector128<int> sum = default;
while (data.Length >= Vector128<int>.Count)
{
sum += Vector128.Create(data);
data = data.Slice(Vector128<int>.Count);
} int result = Vector128.Sum(sum);
foreach (int t in data) result += t;
return result;
}
There is also steady work bringing CoreCLR to WebAssembly in the browser, which is opt-in this preview via <UseMonoRuntime>false</UseMonoRuntime> and not yet wired up for AOT.
Libraries: JSON Lines, full outer joins, and friends
The library additions in Preview 5 are the ones I think most app developers will actually use. First, System.Text.Json can serialize JSON Lines. If you have ever streamed records to a file or a log pipeline where each line is its own JSON object, you know the awkward dance of writing your own newline handling. Now SerializeAsyncEnumerable with topLevelValues: true does it for you, over both Stream and PipeWriter.
await using var stream = new MemoryStream();
await JsonSerializer.SerializeAsyncEnumerable(stream, GetReadings(), topLevelValues: true);
// {"Id":"sensor-1","Value":21.5}
// {"Id":"sensor-2","Value":22}static async IAsyncEnumerable<Reading> GetReadings()
{
yield return new("sensor-1", 21.5);
yield return new("sensor-2", 22.0);
}
public sealed record Reading(string Id, double Value);
Second, LINQ finally has FullJoin. Full outer joins were the one join you had to hand-roll, and now Enumerable, Queryable, and AsyncEnumerable all have FullJoin. Preview 5 also added tuple-returning overloads for Join, LeftJoin, RightJoin, and GroupJoin, so you can deconstruct results inline.
var rows = catalog.FullJoin(
sales,
product => product.Sku,
sale => sale.Sku,
(product, sale) => new
{
Sku = product?.Sku ?? sale!.Sku,
ProductName = product?.Name ?? "(not in catalog)",
QuantitySold = sale?.Quantity ?? 0,
});A grab bag of other genuinely handy additions: EqualityComparer<T>.Create now takes a key selector, so building a HashSet keyed on one property is a one-liner; Random gained generic NextInteger<T> and NextBinaryFloat<T>; StringBuilder.MoveChunks transfers content to a new builder in O(1) and acts as an ownership boundary; Process.ReadAllLines reads interleaved stdout and stderr synchronously, and KillOnParentExit now works on Linux and Android; and System.Security.Cryptography.X25519DiffieHellman brings X25519 key agreement into the box. MediaTypeNames also picked up Video constants like Mp4 and WebM.
var users = new HashSet<User>(
EqualityComparer<User>.Create(user => user!.Email, StringComparer.OrdinalIgnoreCase));
public sealed record User(string Email, string DisplayName);SDK, CLI, EF Core, and Blazor
The SDK story this cycle is mostly about file-based apps growing up. You can now split a file-based app across multiple files with the #:ref directive (transitive references work), and #:include/#:exclude no longer need feature flags. Package and NuGet commands understand file-based app paths too, so dotnet package add app.cs SomePackage works before you ever convert to a project. dotnet new now bundles the MCP Server template, console apps that target net11.0 get System.Net.Http.Json in their implicit usings, and there is an opt-in SDK vulnerability and end-of-life check you can turn on with <CheckSdkVulnerabilities>true</CheckSdkVulnerabilities>.
// app.cs
#:ref lib.cs
Console.WriteLine(MyLib.Greeter.Greet("World"));// lib.cs
namespace MyLib;
public static class Greeter
{
public static string Greet(string name) => $"Hello, {name}!";
}
EF Core got dotnet ef support for file-based apps ( — file and — startup-file), a .config/dotnet-ef.json configuration file, and a new EF1004 analyzer that warns when you use ToAsyncEnumerable() on an IQueryable<T> (which runs synchronously) instead of AsAsyncEnumerable(). SQL Server compatibility level 160 (SQL Server 2022) is now the default, and generated C# uses file-scoped namespaces.
